  "prompt": "Are there ways to not let depression affect your schoolwork?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're feeling this way. Balancing schoolwork while dealing with depression can be challenging, but there are strategies that may help you manage both:\n\n1. **Seek Support:**\n   - **Talk to Someone:** Reach out to a trusted friend, family member, or counselor. Sharing how you feel can provide relief and support.\n   - **Professional Help:** Consider speaking with a mental health professional who can offer tailored strategies and, if needed, treatment options.\n\n2. **Organize and Prioritize:**\n   - **Create a Schedule:** Break your tasks into smaller, manageable steps and set realistic deadlines.\n   - **Prioritize Tasks:** Focus on completing the most important or urgent assignments first to reduce feeling overwhelmed.\n\n3. **Develop Healthy Habits:**\n   - **Regular Routine:** Establish a daily routine that includes time for studying, breaks, meals, and sleep.\n   - **Exercise:** Physical activity can boost your mood and energy levels. Even short walks can make a difference.\n   - **Balanced Diet:** Eating nutritious meals can improve your overall well-being and concentration.\n\n4. **Manage Stress:**\n   - **Mindfulness and Relaxation:** Practices like meditation, deep breathing exercises, or yoga can help reduce stress.\n   - **Take Breaks:** Incorporate short breaks during study sessions to rest and recharge your mind.\n\n5. **Academic Adjustments:**\n   - **Communicate with Educators:** Let your teachers or professors know what you're going through. They may offer extensions or additional support.\n   - **Use School Resources:** Many schools provide counseling services, academic advising, and support groups.\n\n6. **Limit Distractions:**\n   - **Study Environment:** Create a quiet, organized space dedicated to studying to help maintain focus.\n   - **Set Boundaries:** Limit time on social media or other distractions that can interfere with your study time.\n\n7. **Be Kind to Yourself:**\n   - **Set Realistic Goals:** Acknowledge that it's okay not to be perfect. Celebrate small achievements.\n   - **Allow Rest:** Give yourself permission to take breaks and rest when needed without feeling guilty.\n\n8. **Stay Connected:**\n   - **Social Interaction:** Maintaining connections with friends and family can provide emotional support and reduce feelings of isolation.\n\nRemember, you're not alone, and help is available. Please consider reaching out to a mental health professional or someone you trust to discuss how you're feeling.",
